    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-06-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="116"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d116">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.6812a/10</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the Greek
                        Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Simopoulos</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-06-06">June 6,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of May 19, 1930 (numbered 898),<note n="6" xml:id="d116fn6">Not
                        printed.</note> by which you communicated to me the gratifying information
                    that your Government is ready to conclude a treaty of arbitration and a treaty
                    of conciliation with the Government of the United States of America in
                    accordance with the drafts thereof which were transmitted to your Legation in
                    the Department’s note of April 23, 1928.</p>
                <p>Understanding that it is your wish that the two treaties be done in both the
                    English and French languages, I am enclosing for your consideration French
                    equivalents of the English drafts of the two treaties.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d116fn8">Not printed.</note> These follow, <hi rend="italic">mutatis
                        mutandis</hi>, the French text of the treaties of arbitration and
                    conciliation concluded between the United States and <pb facs="0262" n="168"
                        xml:id="pg_168"/> Rumania on March 1 [<hi rend="italic">21</hi>], 1929.<note
                        n="7" xml:id="d116fn7">
                        <ref target="frus1929v03#pg_751">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 751</ref> and <ref
                            target="frus1929v03#pg_753">753</ref>.</note> If these be satisfactory
                    to you, I shall, upon being so informed, direct the preparation of the two
                    treaties for signature and be happy to fix a time convenient to you for their
                    signatures.</p>
                <p>Should you deem it desirable to suggest any changes in the French text of the
                    treaties, the Department will be glad to consider them.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. P. Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
